## Known Limitations

- Manual database checks (role privileges, RLS policies) cannot be fully automated
- Some system-level checks require elevated privileges
- Config file access requires appropriate file permissions
- Performance depends on database size (large databases may take longer)

## Troubleshooting

### "Permission denied" errors

These typically occur when running as non-root user:
- Try: `sudo pgpycis -U postgres -h localhost`
- Or configure sudoers: `sudo install -m 0440 pgpycis.sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/pgpycis`

### Database connection errors

```bash
# Verify connectivity first
psql -U postgres -h localhost -c "SELECT version();"

# Then try pgpycis with verbose output
pgpycis -U postgres -h localhost -f text 2>&1 | head -30
```

### JSON parsing errors

If you see JSON parsing errors from bash checks:
- Verify bash_checks.sh is executable: `chmod +x pgpycis/checks/bash_checks.sh`
- Test directly: `bash pgpycis/checks/bash_checks.sh`

